\part{Phonology}

\section*{Types of sounds}

\paragraph{Consonants}

Danetian has 20 consonant phonemes: six plosives, six fricatives, two
affricates, and six sonorants. These phonemes are organized in the table
below.

\begin{center}
\begin{tabular}{l|cccc}
	\toprule
	~ & Labial & Dental & Palatal & Velar \\
	\midrule
	Plosive & \ipa{p~b} & \ipa{t~d} & ~ & \ipa{k~g} \\
	Affricate & ~ & ~ & \ipa{tʃ~dʒ} & ~ \\
	Fricative & \ipa{f~v} & \ipa{s~z} & \ipa{ʃ} & \ipa{x} \\
	Nasal & \ipa{m} & \ipa{n} & \ipa{ɲ} & ~ \\
	Rhotic & ~ & \ipa{r} & ~ & ~ \\
	Approximant & ~ & \ipa{l} & \ipa{j} & ~ \\
	\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{center}

\paragraph{Vowels}

Danetian has the very common five-vowel system, summarized in the table below.
There is no vowel length distinction.

\begin{center}
\begin{tabular}{l|ccc}
	\toprule
	~ & Front & Central & Back \\
	\midrule
	Close & i & ~ & u \\
	Mid & e & ~ & o \\
	Open & ~ & a & ~ \\
	\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{center}

The vowels \ipa{/a~e~o/} can also be combined with \ipa{/i~u/} to form the
following five falling diphthongs:

\begin{center}
\begin{tabular}{c|cc}
	\toprule
	~ & \ipa{i} & \ipa{u} \\
	\midrule
	\ipa{a} & \ipa{ai̯} & \ipa{au̯} \\
	\ipa{e} & \ipa{ei̯} & \ipa{eu̯} \\
	\ipa{o} & \ipa{oi̯} & ~ \\
	\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{center}

\paragraph{Allophones}

Each phoneme can have several allophones depending on the surrounding context.
The points below summarize how the phonemes are pronounced in the standard
dialect of Danetian. But of course, this is not the only way to pronounce the
language, since there are other dialects. Thus, the reader is encouraged to
pronounce the language in whichever way sounds most beautiful to them.
\begin{itemize}
	\item Whenver \ipa{/s/} appears between vowels or before a voiced
		consonant, it is pronounced as \ipa{[z]}. Otherwise, it is
		pronounced as \ipa{[s]} by default. Compare
		\lan{nefesos} \ipa{['nɛ.fɛ.zos]} \qt{of the cloud},
		\lan{fesor} \ipa{[fɛ'zor]} \qt{hand},
		\lan{tusontis} \ipa{['tu.zon.tis]} \qt{thousand},
		\lan{esvos} \ipa{['ɛz.vos]} \qt{horse},
		\lan{donvos} \ipa{['don.vos]} \qt{number}.
	\item \ipa{/r/} is pronounced as \ipa{[r]} by default, but as \ipa{[ɾ]}
		between vowels. Compare
		\lan{pater} \ipa{[pa'tɛr]} \qt{father},
		\lan{kruros} \ipa{['kru.ɾos]} \qt{bloody}.
	\item \ipa{/l/} is pronounced as \ipa{[l]} by default, but as \ipa{[ɫ]}
		at the end of a word, before a consonant, or before \ipa{/o/}
		or \ipa{/u/}. Compare
		\lan{lana} \ipa{['la.na]} \qt{wool},
		\lan{luvos} \ipa{['ɫu.vos]} \qt{love},
		\lan{lokus} \ipa{['ɫo.kus]} \qt{lake},
		\lan{Michael} \ipa{[mi.xa'ɛɫ]} \qt{Michael},
		\lan{Vilmos} \ipa{['viɫ.mos]} \qt{William}.
	\item \ipa{/x/} is pronounced as \ipa{[x~h]}.
	\item \ipa{/e/} is pronounced as \ipa{[ɛ]} by default, but as \ipa{[e]}
		whenever the following syllable contains \ipa{/i/} or
		\ipa{/j/}. Compare
		\lan{preseti} \ipa{['prɛ.ze.ti]} \qt{he asks},
		\lan{kreva} \ipa{['krɛ.va]} \qt{raw blood},
		\lan{drageti} \ipa{['dra.ge.ti]} \qt{he drags}.
	\item \ipa{/o/} is always pronounced as \ipa{[o]}.
\end{itemize}

\section*{Orthography}

\paragraph{Graphemes}

Danetian orthography uses all 26 letters of the international Latin alphabet.
Most of the letters follow the International Phonetic Alphabet closely. The
exceptions are summarized in the table below, along with other remarks.

\begin{multicols}{2}
\begin{itemize}
	\item \ipa{⟨c⟩: /k/} always
	\item \ipa{⟨g⟩: /g/} always
	\item \ipa{⟨h⟩: /x/}
	\item \ipa{⟨nj⟩: /ɲ/}
	\item \ipa{⟨t⟩: /t/} always
	\item \ipa{⟨qu⟩: /kw/}
	\item \ipa{⟨w⟩: /v/}
	\item \ipa{⟨x⟩: /ks/}
	\item \ipa{⟨y⟩: /i/}
	\item \ipa{⟨ch⟩: /x/} always
	\item \ipa{⟨ph⟩: /f/}
	\item \ipa{⟨th⟩: /t/}
\end{itemize}
\end{multicols}

\paragraph{Stress accent}

Danetian has a stress accent, much like Modern Greek, Spanish, and Russian.
Every word has exactly one stressed syllable, pronounced stronger than the
other syllables. Only the last three syllables of a word have the possibility
of carrying stress, much like in Modern Greek.

In writing, the stress is marked by an acute accent, as in
\lan{natúra} \ipa{[na'tu.ɾa]} \qt{nature},
or it can simply be inferred, as in
\lan{anapreseti} \ipa{[a.na'prɛ.ze.ti]} \qt{he prays}.
The orthographic rules for denoting stress are the following:
\begin{enumerate}
	\item Stress can only fall in the last three syllables.
	\item If stress is unmarked in writing, then it is assumed that it
		falls as far back as it can. Compare
		\lan{danetiska} \ipa{[da'ne.tis.ka]} \qt{Danetian language},
		\lan{bena} \ipa{['bɛ.na]} \qt{woman},
		\lan{en} \ipa{['ɛn]} \qt{in}.
	\item ... unless it ends in a consonant grapheme other than
		\ipa{⟨m⟩}, \ipa{⟨n⟩}, \ipa{⟨s⟩}, or \ipa{⟨t⟩}, in which case
		it is assumed that the stress falls 
\end{enumerate}

