\paragraph{Twenty and beyond}

Every other numeral inflects like a typical noun.
\begin{multicols}{2}
\begin{itemize}
	\item \lan{vidsant} (\Num): twenty
	\item \lan{tridsont} (\Num): thirty
	\item \lan{petvardsont} (\Num): forty
	\item \lan{pempedsont} (\Num): fifty
	\item \lan{svedsont} (\Num): sixty
	\item \lan{septandsont} (\Num): seventy
	\item \lan{oktodsont} (\Num): eighty
	\item \lan{nevandsont} (\Num): ninety
	\item \lan{satón} (\Num): hundred
	\item \lan{tusontis} (\Num): thousand
\end{itemize}
\end{multicols}

The numerals from twenty to ninety inflect like a consonantal-stem noun, and
they always remain in the singular: \lan{svedsont \~ svedsontam \~ svedsonte}.
The numerals \lan{satón} and \lan{tusontis} inflect like a consonantal-stem and
\lan{i}-stem noun, respectively, but they can be either singular or plural.

\paragraph{Complement of a numeral}

A numeral can describe a noun, just like an adjective would:
\lan{dva benas} (two women), \lan{trins sjarans} (three-{\Acc} cities-{\Acc}),
\lan{svekamos viróm} (six-{\Abl} men-{\Abl}). A numeral and its complement noun
form a noun phrase together. The numeral should agree with the gender of the
its complement noun. However, the case of this noun does not necessarily have
to agree with the case of the numeral. The case of the noun is determined by
these rules:
\begin{itemize}
	\item The case of the whole noun phrase is determined by the case
		of the numeral.
	\item For the numerals \lan{oinos}, \lan{dvo}, \lan{tres}, and
		\lan{petvores}, the complement noun should agree both in case
		and number.
	\item For every other numeral, if the case of the noun phrase is
		either nominative or accusative, the noun should be inflected
		in the genitive plural.
	\item Otherwise, the noun and the numeral should be in full agreement
		in both case and number.
\end{itemize}

Some examples will help clarify this.

\begin{center}
\begin{tabular}{l|lll}
	\toprule
	~ & one man & two men & five men \\
	\midrule
	\Nom
	& \lan{oinos viros} & \lan{dvo viroi} & \lan{pempe viróm} \\
	\Acc
	& \lan{oinom virom} & \lan{dvons virons} & \lan{pempans viróm} \\
	\Gen
	& \lan{oinosjo virosjo} & \lan{dvóm viróm} & \lan{pempóm viróm} \\
	\Abl
	& \lan{oinad virad} & \lan{dvamos viromos} & \lan{pempamos viromos} \\
	\Dat
	& \lan{oinoi viroi} & \lan{dvamos viromos} & \lan{pempamos viromos} \\
	\Loc
	& \lan{oini viri} & \lan{dvasu virosu} & \lan{pempasu virosu} \\
	\Ins
	& \lan{oine vire} & \lan{dvafi virois} & \lan{pempafi virois} \\
	\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{center}

\paragraph{Compound numerals}

Several simple numerals can be arranged to form a compound numeral. In English,
an example of this would be \textit{sixty nine}, or \textit{four hundred and
twenty}. We can also do this in Danetian:
\begin{multicols}{2}
\begin{itemize}
	\item 21: \lan{vidsant oinos}
	\item 42: \lan{petvardsont dvo}
	\item 69: \lan{svedsont nevan}
	\item 96: \lan{nevandsont sveks}
	\item 101: \lan{satón oinos}
	\item 144: \lan{satón petvardsont petvóres}
	\item 200: \lan{dvo satones}
	\item 210: \lan{dvo satones desam}
	\item 365: \lan{tres satones svedsont pempe}
	\item 420: \lan{petvóres satones vidsant}
	\item 500: \lan{pempe satonóm}
	\item 507: \lan{pempe satonóm septam}
	\item 1001: \lan{tusontis oinos}
	\item 1200: \lan{tusontis dvo satones}
	\item 1418: \lan{tusontis petvóres satones octodesam}
	\item 1999: \lan{tusontis nevan satones nevandsont nevan}
	\item 2000: \lan{dvo tusonties}
	\item 2021: \lan{dvo tusonties vidsant oinos}
	\item 3000: \lan{tres tusonties}
	\item 5000: \lan{pempe tusontióm}
	\item 9999: \lan{nevan tusontióm nevan satonóm nevandsont nevan}
\end{itemize}
\end{multicols}

\section*{Pronouns}

\paragraph{Personal pronouns}
The personal pronouns are classified according to three persons
(\textit{first}, \textit{second}, and \textit{third}), and two numbers
(\textit{singular} and \textit{plural}). The first and second person pronouns
do not inflect according to gender, but the third person pronouns do. There is
also a reflexive pronoun, which does not inflect by number.

