\paragraph{Possessive pronouns}

The possessive pronouns for first and second person inflect just like regular
adjectives, so we will simply list them without showing their inflection
tables.
\begin{multicols}{2}
\begin{itemize}
	\item \Fsg: \lan{menjos}
	\item \Ssg: \lan{tevjos}
	\item \Fpl: \lan{nosjos}
	\item \Spl: \lan{vosjos}
\end{itemize}
\end{multicols}

However, the third person possessive pronouns are equivalent to the genitive of
the third person personal pronouns. That is,
\lan{enosjo, enosjas, enosjo, enosóm, enasóm, enosóm}. These possessives
do not inflect at all.

\paragraph{Pro-adverbs}

A pro-adverb is a word that substitutes an adverb, such as
\textit{when}, \textit{where}, \textit{somewhere}, \textit{like this}, among
others. In Danetian, pro-adverbs refer to the following categories:
\begin{multicols}{2}
\begin{itemize}
	\item location: where?
	\item source: where from?
	\item destination: where to?
	\item time: when?
	\item manner: how?
	\item amount: how much?
\end{itemize}
\end{multicols}

Moreover, every pro-adverb has its own type, and we can tell what type it is
based on the prefix attached to it:
\begin{multicols}{2}
\begin{itemize}
	\item interrogative: \lan{po-}
	\item relative: \lan{jo-}
	\item proximal: \lan{so-}
	\item distal: \lan{to-}
	\item universal: \lan{viso-}
